  "prompt": "Is calibri with font size 9 good for resume?",
  "response": "Using **Calibri with font size 9** for a resume is generally **not recommended**. Here's why:\n\n### 1. **Readability**  \n   - Font size 9 is too small for most readers, especially for printed resumes or when viewed on screens. It can strain the reader's eyes and make your resume difficult to scan quickly.  \n   - Recruiters often spend only a few seconds reviewing a resume, so clarity and legibility are crucial.\n\n### 2. **Professional Standards**  \n   - The standard font size for resumes is **10\u201312 points**, depending on the font. For Calibri, **size 10.5 or 11** is a good balance between readability and fitting content on one page.  \n   - Larger fonts (e.g., 12) are better for printed resumes, while slightly smaller fonts (10.5\u201311) are fine for digital submissions.\n\n### 3. **Consistency**  \n   - While Calibri is a clean, modern, and professional font, pairing it with a size 9 can make your resume look cramped and less polished.  \n   - Ensure headings and section titles are slightly larger (e.g., 12\u201314) to create a clear hierarchy.\n\n### 4. **Space Management**  \n   - If you're using size 9 to fit more content, consider editing your resume to be more concise rather than sacrificing readability.  \n   - A well-structured one-page resume is often more effective than a crowded two-page one.\n\n### Recommendation:  \n   - Use **Calibri at size 10.5 or 11** for the body text and slightly larger for headings.  \n   - Prioritize readability and professionalism over cramming content.  \n\nLet me know if you'd like tips on formatting or structuring your resume!",
